[normal]1[bold]              [bold]B[bold]A[bold]CKGROUND[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The RAC is the UK’s most progressive motoring organisation and welcomes the 
[normal]opportunity to provide evidence to the Transport
[normal] Select Committee as part of its
[normal] review of the resilience of the UK’s transport networks during 
[normal]severely 
[normal]adverse winter weather.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The RAC represents m
[normal]ore than seven million members, 
[normal]providing
[normal] services for bot
[normal]h private and business motorists
[normal],
[normal] and is committed to making driving easier, safer, more affordable and more enjoyable for all road users.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We employ more than 1700 patrols providing roadside assistance in the most extreme weather conditions across the UK
[normal] and
[normal],
[normal] therefore
[normal],
[normal] have a good understanding of the impact of adverse weather on the road network. Throughout recent winters, RAC patrols have 
[normal]worked alongside the Highways Agency
[normal], the Police Service 
[normal]and other key stakeholders to 
[normal]maximise the safety
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] road
[normal] users
[normal] 
[normal]at risk in
[normal] 
[normal]treacherous conditions. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]D
[normal]uring 
[normal]periods of 
[normal]sudden snowfall
[normal], 
[normal]when roads 
[normal]can 
[normal]became
[normal] im
[normal]passable
[normal], and immediately afterwards, when roads remain treacherous because of compacted ice, t
[normal]he demand for 
[normal]roadside assistance 
[normal]increases dramatically. 
[normal]During the worst periods in recent winters, national demand has risen to levels
[normal] 
[normal]typically 
[normal]50
[normal]% 
[normal]greater than is normal for the time of year
[normal], 
[normal]with demand 
[normal]as much as 
[normal]100% greater than normal in the worst affected areas.
[normal]In response to the conditions
[normal], 
[normal]the 
[normal]RAC 
[normal]h
[normal]as 
[normal]increased the 
[normal]proportion
[normal] o
[normal]f 4x4 patrol vehicle 
[normal]on its fle
[normal]et progressively over the last three
[normal] years. This i
[normal]nvestment has primarily been in
[normal] 4x4 panel vans rather than specialist 4x4 vehicles. We have also issued snow sock
[normal]s
[normal] or snow chains 
[normal]for
[normal] all of our patrol
[normal] vehicles
[normal],
[normal] whereas historically we have only done so in areas where sever
[normal]e
[normal] winter weather was most common. 
[normal] We believe that many other large fleets have made similar investments to improve
[normal] their response to adverse weather
[normal].
[normal]Our comments a
[normal]re confined to the road network and RAC’s ability to respond to adverse weather.
[normal]&#xa0;
