[normal]3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]GENERAL RESILIENCE OF THE ROAD NETWORK[bold]RAC believes that the ability of the Highways Agency and local authorities to respond to adverse weather and keep the roads operation
[normal]al in the most extreme weather 
[normal]has improved since 
[normal]2009/10. The recommendatio
[normal]ns of the Quarmby report have generally been implemented and 
[normal]have delivered the 
[normal]predicted
[normal] benefits
[normal]. Salt stocks have not run out. Major roads are generally treated in a timely way, but patrols report that the effectiveness with which local roads are kept p
[normal]assable still varies hugely from area to area depending on the priority given to this by local authorities. RAC patrols often have to attend customers on
[normal] minor rural
[normal] or residential roads so this does inhibit service delivery
[normal].
[normal]T
[normal]he Highways Agency 
[normal]has been s
[normal]uccessful in keeping
[normal] 
[normal]the strategic road network functioning
[normal]. The only exceptions have been geographically localised and in highly unusual 
[normal]circumstances
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]FORECASTING OF ADVERSE WEATHER[bold]&#xa0;[bold]RAC is
[normal] best able to respond to adverse we
[normal]a
[normal]ther when 
[normal]the organisation 
[normal]has
[normal] 
[normal]sufficient
[normal] wa
[normal]rning
[normal] to adjust resourcing levels
[normal]. Five
[normal]-day weather forecasts 
[normal]proved to be 
[normal]reasonably 
[normal]accurate and predicted the adverse weather in the 2012/13 winter. 
[normal]In contrast
[normal], 
[normal]16-
[normal]day forecasts were insufficiently accurate to justify commitment of ext
[normal]ra resource. 
[normal]Five
[normal] days provide
[normal]d
[normal] only limited opportunity to adjust working shifts and relocate patrols into areas where demand 
[normal]was
[normal] likely to be greatest.
[normal] 
[normal]The
[normal] ability
[normal], therefore, 
[normal]to predict adverse weather a mini
[normal]mum of two
[normal] weeks ahead would significantly im
[normal]prove RAC’s ability to respond. We anticipate that other organisations 
[normal]facing similar challenges 
[normal]would benefit from improved longer term 
[normal]weather forecasting
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]POTHOLES AND [bold]ROAD MAINTENANCE [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The formation of 
[normal]p
[normal]otholes 
[normal]has been accelerated by
[normal] three
[normal] successive
[normal] harsh winters
[normal] and
[normal] 
[normal]has 
[normal]had a large
[normal] and sustained
[normal] 
[normal]impact on 
[normal]the state of our roads
[normal] across the country.
[normal] 
[normal]This 
[normal]has resulted in added risk to the safety 
[normal]of 
[normal]motorists 
[normal]and their vehicles, 
[normal]particularly for cyclists. These risks are increased when pothol
[normal]es become invisible when roads are flooded or covered by snow. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]M
[normal]otorists regard
[normal] 
[normal]local road maintenance
[normal] as the top priority in transport
[normal] spending and this year there ha
[normal]ve
[normal] been 
[normal]numerous 
[normal]calls 
[normal]for local authorities to improve 
[normal]the speed and effectiveness of 
[normal]pothole repairs. The Department for Transport has provided valuable guidance on addres
[normal]sing the practical problems of p
[normal]otholes in the Highways Maintenance Efficiency Pro
[normal]gramme Report “Prevention is bet
[normal]ter than cur
[normal]e – Pothole Review” published i
[normal]n April 2012
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In 2013 the RAC’s Report on Motoring found that:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This dissatisfaction 
[normal]is greatest
[normal] in 
[normal]rural areas 
[normal]where the 
[normal]quality
[normal] of local
[normal] 
[normal]roads appears to be getting much
[normal] 
[normal]worse
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]according to
[normal] 
[normal]87% of respondents. 
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The RAC 
[normal]has called on the 
[normal]Government to
[normal] 
[normal]ensure more of the 
[normal]£ 
[normal]motoring taxation
[normal] 
[normal]collected centrally by the Treasury
[normal], which totals in excess of £40 billion p.a., 
[normal] is
[normal] 
[normal]made 
[normal]available to
[normal] local authorities to fund the
[normal] 
[normal]maintenance of local roads.
[normal] RAC a
[normal]cknowledges that 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government made additional funding available to address the problems of potholes
[normal],
[normal] but 
[normal]this has not had the desired outcomes and it seems likely that 
[normal]in some ca
[normal]ses 
[normal]this funding has been used to 
[normal]replace, rather than supplement,
[normal] funding from local budgets 
[normal]to address local roads maintenance
[normal]. Earlier
[normal] this
[normal] year
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]RAC 
[normal]called
[normal] on the Government to
[normal] 
[normal]carry out an 
[normal]audit 
[normal]of the
[normal] 
[normal]work required to 
[normal]bring 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]UK’s roads 
[normal]to a state 
[normal]that is fit for purpose and prioritise the funding required to achieve this objective over a realistic timescale.
